[White "INTRODUCTION"]
[Black "Bayonet attack"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E97"]
[Annotator "GM Sipke Ernst"]
[PlyCount "25"]
[EventDate "2018.??.??"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 {This move signifies the start of the King's
Indian.} ({Black has some alternatives at this point, of which one the most
notable one is} 3... d5 {, which leads to the Grunfeld Indian. Mihail Marin
has extensively covered this opening for Modern Chess, so you might want to
check out his databases if you are interested.}) 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 (5. Be2 O-O 6.
Be3 $5 {Is a new line which is very popular at the moment. For details on this
system I can recommend you to have a look at Boris Avrukh's database set that
can also be found on the Modern Chess website.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O (7.
d5 {Leads to the Petrosian system and is another reliable weapon against the
King's Indian. This move has been covered on this website by Aleksander
Delchev.}) 7... Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 {And now we have arrived at an important
juncture. For a long time 9.Ne1 was considered to be the absolute mainline,
but at the start of the 1990s more and more GM's started to focus their
attention on the Bayonet attack which begins with the move} 9. b4 {. The idea
behind this move is simple: White gains space on the Queenside and prepares to
push c4-c5 to create tension which will be unpleasant for Black. Black will
typically try to create a play on the Kingside by preparing ...f7-f5. One of
the benefits of the Bayonet system over the 9.Ne1 line is that Black has to be
cautious for not allowing Nf3-g5, followed by a jump to e6, after which the
knight has to be exchanged for Black's light-squared bishop. In the course of
such events, White has good chances of exploiting the weakened light square
complex.} Nh5 {is historically the mainline and will be deeply analyzed in
CHAPTER 10.} ({In CHAPTER 1 we will look at all the alternatives to the most
frequent choices that Black has available.} 9... Kh8 {is probably the best
option as it comes in useful in many lines. Still, it is hard to believe that
Black can afford to make a waiting move, and I found a way for White to get an
advantage by going for the straightforward} 10. c5) (9... c6 {is another way
to avoid the main battleground and is discussed in CHAPTER 2. There is a high
number of options for White here, but I think that the most principled is to
play} 10. dxc6 {when after} bxc6 (10... Nxc6 {is probably a better move, but
after} 11. a3 {we reach relatively simple positions in which White enjoys the
better pawn structure, and Black can hardly hope for active play. Not the
King's Indian dream for many players on the Black side in my opinion!}) 11. Bg5
{Black experiences problems with his backward d-pawn.}) ({CHAPTER 3 deals with
the move} 9... Ne8 {, which is a favorite of Nakamura and usually leads to
very sharp play. The good news is that White has the better chances. I suggest
to go} 10. a4 f5 (10... a5 11. Ba3 axb4 12. Bxb4 b6 {transposes to a line
where White has good chances and is discussed in CHAPTER 9.}) 11. Nd2 Nf6 12.
c5 {when Black usually goes for} f4 {after which the battle will continue on
both flanks. I think White's attack is faster and that the line is dubious for
Black.}) (9... a5 {Will be the topic of CHAPTER 5-9. White will go} 10. Ba3 {
when we will discuss alternatives to the main moves in CHAPTER 5. CHAPTER 6
will see us deal with 10...b6 11.bxa5 Nh5. (Note that 11.. .Rxa5 12. Bb4 Ra8
13.a4 transposes to later chapters). After 11...Nh5 the Swiss GM Yannick
Pelletier used an interesting concept to beat Nakamura that started with the
move 12.Nd2!? This concept has been analyzed in detail. In the next CHAPTER 7,
we will see how best to handle the line 10...axb4 11.Bxb4 Re8!? This is a
recent try, and it has given me, and probably many other players that have the
Bayonet attack on their repertoire, a lot of headaches. In the end, I found a
good way how to handle the positions and hope you will feel confident to try
the ideas offered in this Chapter. 11...Nd7 is the most popular move at this
juncture and is discussed in CHAPTER 8. The truth is that this way of handling
the position is not so popular anymore, and for a good reason. White has found
a good way of handling such positions, and it usually results in Black having
to wait passively for White's next move. CHAPTER 9, on the other hand, is more
critical. After 11...b6 12.a4 Re8!? Black is preparing to stop White's attack
on the Queenside with some defensive measures that include the move ...Bf8,
followed by a subsequent ...c7-c5. White then gets to choose between two type
of structures: There is dxc6 en passant, after which the play becomes more
open and Black hopes to exploit the weakened dark squares in White's camp, but
White can also leave the position closed with Ba3. Both structures will be
dealt with in this chapter.}) ({In CHAPTER 4 we will discuss a line which
looks similar to the one we have analyzed in the previous chapter. After} 9...
Nd7 {White continues to gain space on the queenside with} 10. a4 {when the
direct} f5 {does not look so great to me at all, as White can go} 11. Ng5 Nf6
12. f3 {When we are looking at a position that resembles what is analyzed in
CHAPTER 10, except that White, wasn't obliged to play the weakening g2-g3. The
analysis shows that White has the better chances in this line.}) {And now
instead of the most popular move 10.Re1, which I think has been analyzed to
the extent that there is hardly anything original to be found in those lines,
I focussed on the move} 10. g3 $5 {, which is a straightforward way of dealing
with ...Nf4, but the downside is that it weakens our kingside. Still, I
believe White can handle such a slight weakening as I believe that after the
critical} f5 11. Ng5 {White will confiscate the light-squared bishop, which
usually is a very important piece for Black in an attack against the White
king.} Nf6 {And here White has to make another decision. Although there is a
case to be made for 12.Bf3, which has been used with success by Kramnik, I
have chosen to focus on the mainline which goes} 12. f3 {After this move the
play becomes incredibly sharp and forcing. This move has been played 30 times
by the strong Dutch GM Loek van Wely, and he scored some impressive wins in
our line. I believe the best Black can do is} f4 {and here White's most
popular move has always been Kg2, but I am advocating the more aggressive} 13.
b5 {. White's results have been quite good in this line and in the analysis in
this Chapter we will see that Black is walking a tightrope.} *

