[White "CHAPTER 1"]
[Black "9...Kh8 and others"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E97"]
[Annotator "GM Sipke Ernst"]
[PlyCount "35"]
[EventDate "2018.??.??"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Kh8 {[%cal Re7g8,Rf6e8,Rf7f5] This is a specialty of the British
Grandmaster Mark Hebden. Black evacuates the g8 square for a knight and
sidesteps any tricks that might happen later on the a2-g8 diagonal. Still, the
move looks too slow to me.} (9... h6 $6 {This move also looks slow. It was
tried once by Judit Polgar so we will have a closer look at it. In my opinion, it is best to continue with} 10. c5 Ne8 11. a4 f5 12. Nd2 Nf6 (12... f4 $2 {
is too early: Black should wait for f2-f3 before closing the center. One of
the 'extras' White has now can be seen after} 13. Nc4 g5 14. Ba3 Nf6 15. cxd6
cxd6 16. b5 Ne8 {and now} 17. Bh5 $1 $18) 13. f3 f4 14. Nc4 {The center is
closed and there is going to be a race in which White's play on the Queenside
should be faster. White has made all logical moves while Black has wasted time
on h7-h6. This is a square which can often be used by a knight (to support the
push g5-g4), rook (attacking h2!) or a bishop. The loss of a mere tempo is a
high price in such a sharp position.} g5 15. Ba3 Ng6 16. b5 dxc5 17. Bxc5 Rf7
18. a5 h5 19. b6 g4 20. Nb5 {White has close to winning position but lost at
the end Anand-Nakamura, 2011}) (9... b6 $6 {Making pawn moves on the side of
the board where White is attacking is not a good idea. The move only speeds up
White's play.} 10. a4 a5 ({Black has to stop the advance on the queenside now,
as after, e.g.} 10... Nd7 $2 11. a5 Rb8 (11... f5 {is typically answered by}
12. Ng5 $1 Nf6 13. axb6 cxb6 14. c5 $1 bxc5 15. bxc5 dxc5 16. Qb3 {and White
is nearly winning}) 12. axb6 axb6 13. Ra7 $16 {Black still hasn't started any
counterplay on the kingside.}) 11. bxa5 Rxa5 (11... bxa5 $6 {would be a
mistake as it would allow} 12. c5 $1) 12. Nd2 Nd7 (12... Ne8 {has also been
tried:} 13. Nb3 Ra8 14. a5 c5 (14... bxa5 15. Nxa5 Bd7 16. c5 $1 $16) 15. axb6
Rxa1 16. Nxa1 Qxb6 {Hernandez Carmenates-Rahul, Islamabad 2017} 17. Qb3 $146
Qxb3 18. Nxb3 {and White remains better due to the space advantage. Black
especially has difficulties finding good squares for the knights.}) 13. Nb3 Ra8
{There have been approximately 50 games with this position, and the score is
very encouraging for White. After the logical} 14. a5 {Black only managed to
score 5,5 points from 31 games!} bxa5 15. Nxa5 {[%cal Ga5c6] (threatening Nc6)}
Rb8 (15... Ba6 16. Be3 f5 {and now there is nothing wrong with the move f3,
but even more powerful is} 17. Nc6 $1 Nxc6 18. dxc6 Nf6 19. Bg5 {[%csl Ra6] as
Black will experience huge problems with the bishop on a6.}) 16. Be3 f5 17. f3
f4 18. Bf2 g5 {This position resembles a Mar del Plata Be3 line, but White is
much faster here because of the unnecessary pawn play by Black on the
Queenside.} 19. Nb5 $16) (9... a6 $6 {[%csl Rb6] This is probably even worse
than 9...b6. This move unnecessarily weakens the b6-square. Moreover, I am not
entirely sure what Black is trying to achieve with this move.} 10. c5 Ne8 (
10... Nh5 11. Nd2 ({Somehow going down the road of our mainline (see Chapter
10) doesn't really work:} 11. g3 f5 12. Ng5 Nf6 13. Bf3 $2 h6 14. Ne6 Bxe6 15.
dxe6 fxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 d5 $1 $15 {and Black is successfully fighting
for light square control. The nice center and weak e6 pawn outweighs the
bishop pair.}) 11... Nf4 12. Nc4 Nxe2+ 13. Qxe2 f5 14. f3 {[%csl Rb6][%cal
Gc1e3,Gc5d6]} f4 {else White plays Be3, followed by cxd6 and the b6 weakness
will make itself felt.} 15. a4 g5 16. Ba3 $16)) (9... c5 $2 {looks very
reasonable at first sight but leads to a strategically lost position after} 10.
bxc5 (10. dxc6 {is also possible, and transposes to 9...c6 10.dxc6, which is
discussed in CHAPTER 2.}) 10... dxc5 11. Be3 b6 12. a4 Ne8 13. a5 Rb8 {
Galkiewicz-Kruszunski, 2000} 14. Qb3 $146 {[%cal Gf1b1] followed by Rfb1}) 10.
c5 {That is why we play b2-b4 in the first place. Might as well carry on with
it!} Neg8 {This move was many times played by British GM Mark Hebden.} (10...
Ne8 {is the alternative. We could also come to this position via a different
move order: 9...Ne8 10.c5 Kh8. I suggest continuing} 11. Nd2 f5 12. a4 Ng8 {
again transposing to our mainline.}) ({It looks strange to go} 10... Nh5 {
anyway, as it looks like an inferior version of the mainlines, but for some
strange reason, matters are not so easy. 11.g3 is not a good move and 11.Re1
looks promising but somehow the inclusion of ...Kh8 and c5 does not always
favor White. Best is to follow the game Safarli-Mamedov, 2016, where White
continued} 11. Nd2 Nf4 12. Nc4 f5 13. f3 {[%cal Ra2a4,Rc1a3] when White is
better.}) 11. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Rd1h5] Stopping ...Nh5 ideas.} Ne8 12. a4 f5 13.
Ba3 Ngf6 (13... Nh6) (13... fxe4 14. Ndxe4) 14. b5 (14. f3 {is probably good
as well.}) 14... Bh6 (14... f4 $2 {This leads to a very bad version of the 9...
Ne8 line. After} 15. a5 b6 16. axb6 axb6 17. cxb6 cxb6 18. Bb4 {White has a
winning advantage}) 15. a5 Bxd2 16. Qxd2 Nxe4 (16... f4 {was seen in
Werle-Stange, 2002 and is no improvement as White can go} 17. b6 $18) 17. Nxe4
fxe4 18. b6 $18 {Lputian-Donguines, 1994} *

