1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 c6 $5 {With this move Black stops the advance of c4-c5, but it also
somewhat goes against the principle of avoiding pawn moves where the opponent
is the stronger side. It is analyzed in the book 'Bologan's King's Indian' by,
you probably guessed it, Victor Bologan.} 10. dxc6 $5 {There are good
alternatives, but the text move is the most principled.} Nxc6 (10... bxc6 $6 {
is worse. After} 11. Bg5 h6 $2 (11... Be6) (11... a5 12. b5 cxb5 13. cxb5 (13.
Bxf6 {was played in Belozerov-Inarkiev, Vladivostok 2012, but there is no need
to take on f6 immediately.}) 13... Bb7 {and here White has two options:} 14.
Nd2 ({I also looked at} 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Bc4 Rc8 16. Qd3 Qc7 ({Black can also
sharpen the game with} 16... d5 $5 {but the ensuing complications favour White.
} 17. exd5 {this is forced.} (17. Nxd5 $2 {loses the exchange after} Nxd5 18.
Bxd5 Bxd5 19. exd5 e4) 17... e4 18. Nxe4 Bxa1 19. Rxa1 Kh8 $1 {This position
looks very promising for White, but there are some back rank problems.} ({
of course not} 19... Nxd5 $2 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Qxd5 Qxd5 22. Nf6+ Kg7 23. Nxd5
Rc5 24. Ne3 Rxb5 {and this position is probably a technical win.}) ({worse is} 
19... Kg7 $2 20. Qd4+ f6 21. Nfg5 $1 {and after the forced} Bxd5 22. Bxd5 Qxd5
23. Qxd5 Nxd5 24. Ne6+ Kf7 25. Nxf8 Kxf8 26. Rd1 {White should have good
winning chances in this endgame.}) 20. Nfg5 Bxd5 21. Qd4+ f6 22. Bxd5 Qxd5 23.
Qxd5 Nxd5 24. Ne6 Rce8 25. Nxf8 Rxe4 {this is just a sample line. In the final
position, White is playing for two results only. I cannot believe that there
are King's Indian players that are dying to defend such an endgame for Black
straight out of the opening.}) 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 {and White is probably
slightly better here as well.}) 14... h6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nc4 d5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5
(17... Nxd5 18. exd5 Bxd5 19. a4 {and this position looks to me to be somewhat
unpleasant for Black. White has a protected passed pawn on b5, and also the
d5-square is weakened. White can continue with moves such as Ne3 and Bc4, with
the goal to occupy the d5-square.}) 18. exd5 Nxd5 {it seems that Black is
active enough, but after} 19. Qe1 $1 {I didn't find a good follow up for Black.
}) 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Qd2 Kg7 14. Rfd1 a5 15. b5 cxb5 16. cxb5 Be6 {
Matjushin-Dolzhikova, Kiev 1998 and here I don't see much wrong with} 17. Qxd6
$16 {when White is a pawn up, and the b-pawn is a dangerous asset, while
Black's bishops hardly provide any counterplay.} (17. Rac1)) 11. Rb1 Bg4 (11...
Nd4 12. Be3 Nxe2+ 13. Qxe2 Be6 14. Rfd1 Qc7 {and now White has the following
idea:} 15. c5 $1 dxc5 16. bxc5 $14 {[%csl Gd6] White has several attractive
options here. Knight jumps to b5 and d5 being the most prominent ones.}) (11...
a5 12. b5 Nd4 13. Be3 ({I am also not convinced that Black is equalizing after
} 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Qxd4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Bxc3 16. Be3 $1 $146 {as taking the
exchange with} Bf5 (16... Re8 {is better, but even so White is better after
the simple} 17. Qc2) 17. Qxb7 Bxb1 18. Rxb1 {gives White too much play.}) 13...
Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 $14 {White has a nice space advantage and a clear target on d6
to attack.}) 12. Be3 Rc8 13. a4 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nd4 15. Be2 a5 16. Qd2 ({Even} 
16. b5 $5 {is a playable pawn sacrifice:} Nxe2+ (16... Nd7 $5) 17. Qxe2 Qc7 18.
c5 dxc5 19. Bg5 Rfd8 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Nd5 Qd6 22. Rfd1 {and, the permanent
knight on d5, provides White with enough compensation for the pawn, although
probably not more.}) 16... Nd7 17. Nd5 axb4 18. Rxb4 Nc5 19. Bd3 $14 *

