1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Ne8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd6][%cal Rf7f5] This move is more popular than 9...
Nd7. Especially Nakamura had a lot of success with the black pieces. This,
however, was usually not due to the quality of his positions after the opening
stage.} 10. c5 {Since Black is not preventing our main idea I suggest we carry
on with it.} f5 (10... a5 11. Ba3 {transposes to CHAPTER 5.}) (10... Kh8 {
[%emt 0:00:01] transposes to 9...Kh8. See CHAPTER}) 11. Nd2 ({The reason why
White doesn't play} 11. Ng5 {here is that the knight on e8 is rather well
placed to meet the jump to e6. After} h6 12. Ne6 Bxe6 13. dxe6 fxe4 14. cxd6 ({
Black also has a good position after} 14. Nxe4 d5) 14... Nxd6 {White maybe has
enough compensation, but Black has had good results here, so maybe his
position is easier to play.}) 11... Nf6 ({Black has also played} 11... f4 {
, which is a bit inflexible as it releases the tension in the center right
away. Therefore I don't like it very much, but it appeared in close to 200
games. There is a big chance that we will end up in the mainline after} 12. Nc4
g5 13. a4 {and now 13...Nf6 transposes back into the mainline, but Black can
also continue} Ng6 {when I suggest you go} 14. Ba3 {[%cal Ga3d6] from where
the bishop increases the pressure on d6. For Black it is now tough to push the
kingside pawns, so probably he should continue with} Nh4 {when I like} 15. Kh1
$5 g4 (15... f3 {looks attractive but doesn't achieve much:} 16. Bxf3 Nxf3 17.
gxf3 Qf6 18. Rg1 $1 Qxf3+ 19. Qxf3 Rxf3 20. Rg3 Rxf2 21. Rxg5 $16) 16. g3 f3
17. Bd3 Ng6 18. Qd2 {when I don't see a way for Black to continue the attack,
while White's initiative on the queenside keeps growing.}) 12. a4 f4 (12... Rf7
$5 {Black defends the weak c7-point in advance, and the dark-squared bishop
can come to f8 to support d6. It can also be seen as a clever waiting move
since there is no Nc4 for White and if White plays 13.f3, then 13...f4 is
likely to transpose to lines where Black has fewer problems and are not in our
repertoire. I like} 13. a5 $5 (13. Ba3 g5 $5 {compare to Anand-Nakamura,
Bilbao 2011 - see 12...g5}) 13... Bh6 {This move gave me some headaches as now
both 13.f3 and 13.Nc4 are not very attractive. The engine likes all sorts of
moves like 14.Bc4 and maybe if you do some digging here this really is a
strong move. For now, I sugggest} (13... Bf8 14. f3 f4 15. Nc4) (13... f4 14.
Nc4 g5 15. Nb5 $1 Nxe4 16. Bd3 $1 Bf5 (16... a6 17. Nxc7 Qxc7 18. Bxe4 $18) (
16... Nxf2 17. Rxf2 e4 18. Bxe4 Bxa1 19. cxd6 cxd6 20. Nbxd6 Rf8 21. Bxf4 {
when White has a very powerful initiative.}) 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. cxd6 Bxd5 19.
dxe7 Rxe7 20. Ncd6 $1 c6 21. Nf5 Rd7 22. Nc3 Bxg2 (22... Bc4 23. Qc2 Bxf1 24.
Kxf1 $16) 23. Qb3+ Bd5 24. Nxd5 cxd5 25. Nxg7 Kxg7 26. Qh3 $1 {when the three
pawns are not enough for the piece.}) 14. Bb2 Bxd2 {taking the pawn is critical
} (14... Nxe4 15. Ndxe4 fxe4 16. Nxe4 $14) 15. Qxd2 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 fxe4 17. b5 {
[%cal Ra1a4] followed by Ra4. Quite an unusual rooklift in the King's Indian!
White has the better chances.}) (12... g5 {Nakamura tried this move in a game
against Anand in 2011. In a previous game, Nakamura had played 12...f4 against
Kramnik, so I think he played 12...g5 just to avoid Anand's preparation. Anand
continued} 13. Nc4 $1 {[%csl Rg5] which is threatening to take on g5 and
invites to transpose back into the mainline with 13...f4. Instead, the game
went} h6 $6 {Which looks rather slow, but maybe the idea behind this move is
to wait for White to play f3. After that move Black does not have to worry
about the exchange of light squared bishops, as we see is thematic in some of
our mainlines in this file. But the downside of this move is that ...h6 is not
very useful in a pawn storm to mate the White king.} 14. f3 f4 15. Ba3 Ng6 16.
b5 dxc5 17. Bxc5 Rf7 18. a5 {Anand-Nakamura, Bilbao 2011 and Anand quickly got
a winning position but lost the game anyway. That is also typical King's
Indian I am afraid...}) (12... Bh6 {This move has also been tried several
times and looks interesting. The best reaction seems to be} 13. a5 $1 Bxd2 {
A strategically risky decision, but it also looks the most principled to me.
If Black switches to 13...f4 then bringing the bishop to h6 was just a loss of
time.} (13... fxe4 14. Ndxe4 Bxc1 15. Rxc1 Nf5 16. Bc4 {is also a little
better for White. Black did manage to achieve his dark-squared bishop, but
White made good progress on the queenside.}) (13... Rf7 {transposes to 12...Rf7
}) 14. Bxd2 Nxe4 ({or} 14... fxe4 15. Bg5) 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Bg5 {and I like
White.}) 13. Nc4 g5 14. Nb5 $5 {A fascinating idea, which was first tried by
Jan Werle in a game against Vallejo Pons. That game ended in a loss for Jan,
but he got a good advantage out of the opening and only made some mistakes
later on. The most popular move is 14. Ba3 but I believe the move given as our
mainline is more promising.} Nxe4 (14... Ne8 {was played recently by the
strong Danish GM Mads Andersen played this move against me. White can continue
as follows:} 15. Ba3 Ng6 16. Bg4 Bxg4 (16... Nh4 17. Bxc8 Rxc8 {Werle-Vallejo
Pons, Wijk aan Zee 2007. White has several good moves here, but I like} 18. Qg4
{the most.}) 17. Qxg4 Rf7 18. f3 $5 {It looks somewhat scary to close the
retreat for the White queen but engines confirm the queen is perfectly safe on
the h3-g8 diagonal.} Bf6 19. Rfd1 Be7 20. Rac1 $16 {and White had a promising
position in Ernst-Andersen, Dutch league 2018}) 15. f3 a6 16. Nxc7 Nc3 (16...
Qxc7 $2 17. fxe4 {already looks hopeless for Black, as White's attack is
raging on.}) 17. Qe1 Nxe2+ (17... Qxc7 18. cxd6 Nxe2+ 19. Qxe2 {transposes to
17...Nxe2+}) 18. Qxe2 Qxc7 19. cxd6 Qd8 20. dxe7 Qxe7 21. Bb2 {This position
was reached in the game Buhmann-Sadilek, 2014. White is slightly better.} *

