1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nd7 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Rf7f5] With this move Black stops c4-c5 for the
moment and prepares his usual Kingside play with ...f7-f5. Although the move
is fairly logical it has never been very popular. White has several promising
plans here. Sacrificing a pawn with c4-c5 is very interesting for example.} 10.
a4 f5 (10... a5 {is also possible, and likely transposes to other lines,
although there are some individual tries for both sides.} 11. Ba3 axb4 (11...
f5 12. Ng5 Nf6 13. bxa5 $5 $146 Rxa5 (13... h6 {is possible and after} 14. Ne6
Bxe6 15. dxe6 {there is an interesting battle where White fights for light
square domination and Black enjoys the better pawn structure. I think in this
case White's initiative is more important. Here are some sample lines:} Rxa5 (
15... fxe4 16. Rb1 $36) (15... Nxe4 16. Nxe4 fxe4 17. Rb1 $36) 16. Bb4 Ra8 17.
c5 d5 {forced} 18. exd5 Nfxd5 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 {and now there is more than one
way to secure an advantage, but I like} 20. c6 $1 Nxb4 21. cxb7 Rb8 (21... Qxd1
22. Rfxd1 Rab8 23. Rd7 $16) 22. Qb3 Qe7 23. Rfd1 $16)) 12. Bxb4 {and we have
transposed to 9...a5 10.Ba3 ab4:11.Bb4: Nd7 12.a4}) (10... h6 $2 {This seems
to me to be too slow. It was however played once by Judit Polgar, who is a
huge expert on the Black side of the King's Indian.} 11. Ba3 f5 12. c5 Nf6 13.
Nd2 g5 (13... fxe4 14. Ndxe4 Nf5 {This is another common structure in the
Bayonet. Black gets the d4-square for a knight while White has firm control
over e4. The latter is usually of more importance as in most cases the knight
on d4 lacks support from other pieces.} 15. b5 b6 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6
18. Ne4 Be7 {This was all seen in Karjakin-Polgar, 2009. Here I like to
continue with} 19. Rc1 {as after} Bb7 20. Rc6 $1 $16 {is a very promising
exchange sacrifice.}) 14. b5 Ng6 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Nc4 Ne8 17. Bh5 $1 $16) 11.
Ng5 $1 {one of the advantages of the Bayonet attack over other systems like 9.
Ne1 or Nd2 is that Black always has to worry about the text move.} (11. Nd2 {
is an alternative, when after} Nf6 (11... a5) 12. c5 {we have transposed to
the mainlines of 9... Ne8, however, White should also be prepared for 11...a5})
11... Nf6 {Now White should be prepared for the move ... h7-h6. It forces
White to jump to e6 after which White will collect the bishop pair. I like} 12.
f3 {as in the mainline we are playing similarly. White has excellent results
from this position. Note that 12.Bf3 is a good alternative and also has
brought White a lot of success.} h6 (12... f4 13. c5 h6 14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. dxe6
d5 16. exd5 Nfxd5 17. Nxd5 Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Nxd5 19. Bc4 c6 20. Rd1 $14) (12... c6
13. a5) 13. Ne6 Bxe6 14. dxe6 c6 15. Be3 $14 {White has a good position. The
positions are similar to the 9...Nh5 mainline, except for that White didn't
have to play g3.} *

