1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5 10. Ba3 {In this file we will look at some of the alternatives to
the main move 10....axb4 and 10...b6 of which} Nh5 {is the most original.} (
10... Ne8 {Another way to reach this position would be 9...a5 10.Ba3 Ne8. The
most consistent is to continue with} 11. c5 axb4 (11... f5 {allows} 12. b5 $1 {
We will see a similar idea after 10...Nh5 11.c5 f5 12.b5! although the knight
is probably better placed on e8 as it defends some vital squares.} fxe4 (12...
b6 13. cxb6 cxb6 14. Ng5 $14) 13. Nxe4 Nf5 14. Bd3 {and White is slightly
better.}) 12. Bxb4 f5 (12... dxc5 13. Bxc5 Nd6)) (10... Re8 $5 {The strong
Icelandic GM Hjartarson recently tried this move in a game against Eljanov.
White should play} 11. bxa5 ({one of the ideas behind 10... Re8 is seen in} 11.
c5 $6 axb4 12. Bxb4 dxc5 13. Bxc5 c6 $1 {which occurred in Wantola-Den Hartog,
2015}) 11... Rxa5 12. Bb4 Ra8 13. a4 {[%emt 0:00:07] and we have transposed to
the line 10... axb4 11.Bxb4 Re8, which is discussed in CHAPTER}) (10... Nd7 11.
bxa5 Rxa5 (11... b6 $6 12. Bb4 bxa5 13. Ba3 {leads to a structure which is
very unfavorable for Black. White has good chances to push through c4-c5. and
if} Nc5 {White can continue with} 14. Bxc5 $146 dxc5 15. Ne1 $1 $16 {[%csl Rc5]
}) 12. Bb4 Ra8 {[%emt 0:00:08] and we have transposed to CHAPTER}) (10... b6 {
[%emt 0:00:06] is discussed in CHAPTER 6}) 11. c5 {It has been known for a
while that this is the most testing move. In over 80 games White scored over
65% from this position. You might wonder why in CHAPTER 10 we don't go 10.c5
instead of 10. g3. The inclusion of the moves 9...a5 10. Ba3, however, is very
much in White's favor as it leaves the Black queenside weakened.} ({One of
the main ideas behind 10...Nh5 is that} 11. Re1 {can be answered by} Nf4 12.
Bf1 axb4 13. Bxb4 Bg4 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 c5 $1 16. dxc6 Nxc6 $11) 11... axb4
(11... Nf4 12. b5 $1 b6 13. cxd6 cxd6 14. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Rd6]} ({In the stem
game between Topalov and Judith Polgar, Frankfurt 1999, White continued} 14.
Rc1 {and scored a fine victory. But the text move is even stronger.}) 14... f5
15. Nc4 Rf6 16. Re1 Nxe2+ 17. Rxe2 f4 $2 {This allows a nice tactic that is
worth remembering.} (17... g5 {to give the knight access to g6 seems like a
better try, but still White's position is much better.}) 18. Nxe5 $1 Rf8 (18...
f3 19. Rd2 {doesn't really help}) 19. Nc6 Nxc6 20. dxc6 Be6 21. e5 {and White
was winning in Savchenko-Rechel, Darmstadt 2001}) 12. Bxb4 Nf4 (12... dxc5 13.
Bxc5 Nf4 {is quite tricky: I recommend here} 14. a4 $146 ({Almost all games in
this line continued} 14. Bc4 {but after} Bg4 $1 15. h3 Bh5 {the situation is
rather unclear. In Babula-Hillarp Persson, Gothenburg 2005, White continued 16.
Nb5 and the game eventually ended in a draw. The attempt to improve on the
game with} 16. Kh2 {to deal with the unpleasant pin on the h5-d1 diagonal,
Black can go} g5 17. g3 Nxh3 $1 {when after} 18. Kxh3 g4+ 19. Kh4 $2 {indeed
seems to win a piece, but you will probably get mated after} f5 $1) 14... Bg4 (
14... Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2 {looks good for White, as Black has no counterplay.}) 15.
h3 Bh5 {and compared to the 14.Bc4 line, I think we are happy to have the
bishop on e2 so we can now go} 16. Kh2 $1 Nxe2 17. Qxe2 {and now Black is
forced to take on f3 because} f5 $2 {is met with the very strong} 18. Qa2 $1
$18) 13. cxd6 cxd6 14. Nb5 Ra6 15. Nd2 $1 {The simplest. Now we are not
allowing ...Bg4 and from c4 the knight will put even more pressure on d6.} f5
$6 (15... Bd7 {is a better move, but White also has the upper hand here.} 16.
a4 Nc8 (16... Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2 Nc8 18. Rfc1 $16) {and here White can choose from
many moves, but the simplest is} 17. Bc4 Bh3 18. g3 Bxf1 19. Bxf1 {when White
has more than enough compensation for the exchange}) 16. Bc4 fxe4 17. Nxe4 Nf5
18. Rc1 {and White's position is in great shape} *

