1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5 10. Ba3 b6 {This move is not as popular as it once was, but it
has a logic behind it. Black wants to hold up the c4-c5 advance for as long as
possible. But there is a downside with this move. You may already be familiar
with the rule that one should avoid making pawn moves on the side of the board
where the opponent is stronger. In this case, White will use the b6 pawn as a
hook to break down the queenside with a4-a5.} (10... Nd7 11. bxa5 Rxa5 12. Bb4
Ra8) (10... Nh5 11. c5 $1 axb4 (11... Nf4 12. b5 $1) 12. Bxb4 Nf4 13. cxd6 cxd6
14. Nd2 $1 f5 15. Nb5 Rf6 16. Bc4 g5 17. a4 g4 18. Rc1 Rh6 19. Re1 $1 Bf8 20.
Qb3 $1 $16 {is a line given by Markos in his excellent book 'Beat the KID'.})
11. bxa5 {It it pointless to delay this exchange.} Nh5 $5 {This move was tried
in a game by Nakamura and used to be a pet favorite of the strong Israelian
GM and King's Indian expert Ilja Smirin.} (11... Rxa5 12. Bb4 Ra8 {transposes
to 10...axb4 11.Bxb4 b6} 13. a4) (11... Ne8 $5 {was tried against me recently
by Erwin L'Ami.} 12. Nb5 (12. Bb4 c5 $1) 12... Rxa5 13. Bb4 Ra8 14. a4 f5 15.
Nd2 (15. a5 $6 {is what I played but this cannot be recommended as after} fxe4
16. Ng5 {Ernst-L'Ami, Amsterdam 2018} e3 $1 {Black has the initiative}) 15...
Bh6 16. a5 $5 c5 (16... bxa5 17. Rxa5 Rxa5 18. Bxa5) 17. dxc6 $1 {White is
temporarily sacrificing a pawn, but greatly increases the activity of his
pieces. e.g.} Nxc6 18. Ba3 Nxa5 19. exf5 Bxf5 20. Bf3 Rc8 21. Ne4 Bxe4 22. Bxe4
Nxc4 23. Bb4 {and Black has to be very careful here.}) 12. Nd2 ({The mainline
continues} 12. Re1 {but in general Black's results were quite satisfactory in
this line. Pelletier tried the text move in a game against Nakamura and he
used a novelty to score a crushing victory in that game.}) (12. Nb5 {1-0 (40)
Van Wely, L (2675)-Smirin, I (2661) Philadelphia USA 2011 [Vigorito, D]}) 12...
Nf4 13. axb6 $1 {White is sacrificing a piece, but manages to break through on
the queenside right away.} Rxa3 (13... Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 {is only helpful to
White.}) 14. Nb5 Ra8 {This is the best square for the rook.} (14... Ra5 $2 {
was played in a game mentioned above when there followed} 15. bxc7 Qd7 16. a4
Ba6 17. Nb3 Bxb5 18. cxb5 Qxc7 19. Nxa5 Qxa5 20. g3 Nxe2+ 21. Qxe2 Bh6 22. Rfb1
Rb8 {[%cal Ge7c8,Gc8b6] Black just wants to play ... Nc8-b6 when matters are
not so clear.} (22... Nc8 23. Rb2 Nb6 24. Rc2 $1 {and the rook will find
itself a nice outpost on c6.}) 23. b6 $1 {A good decision. White stops Black
from setting up some kind of blockade on the queenside by sacrificing another
pawn. The remaining a pawn will prove too strong,} Rxb6 24. Rxb6 Qxb6 25. a5 {
and White went on to win in Pelletier-Nakamura, Skopje 2015}) 15. bxc7 Qd7 16.
a4 Ba6 17. Re1 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 {and the idea is} Bxb5 19. cxb5 Qxc7 20. Rec1 {
when White's compensation is very real.} *


