1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5 10. Ba3 axb4 11. Bxb4 Re8 $5 {is a move that recently has come
into fashion.} 12. a4 $1 ({The straightforward} 12. c5 $6 {doesn't achieve
much because Black has the cunning reply} dxc5 13. Bxc5 c6 $1 {The main point
is that after} 14. d6 {black can answer with} (14. dxc6 {is a better move, but
after} Qa5 $1 (14... Nxc6 15. Bc4 {was slightly better for White in
Wantola-Den Hartog, Dutch league 2015}) 15. Bxe7 Rxe7 {[%cal Gb7c6] Landa-Berg,
German league 2015, followed by ... bxc6 Black has the easier position,
although objectively it should be equal.}) 14... Qa5 $1 15. Rc1 {and here I
think the following move is interesting:} Bg4 $1 $146 16. Nxe5 Bxe2 17. Nxe2
Nxe4 18. d7 Nxc5 $5 19. dxe8=Q+ Rxe8 $44) 12... Bf8 {[%cal Gc7c5,Yf7f5] This
is a critical position and one that has given me a lot of headaches. There
have only been 11 games so far with this position (Black scored 6,5 points)
but I expect many more to come. Black is going to play ...c7-c5 and after the
queenside is closed slowly prepare ...f7-f5. How should White compete against
this plan?} (12... c5 $5 {was tried in a recent encounter. I think it is the
most principled reaction now for White to grab the pawn with} 13. dxc6 $1 $146
(13. Ba3 Ra6 {to me it seems to be an achievement that Black avoided... Bf8 to
get to this structure. Since the dark-squared bishop often returns to g7 Black
saves two tempi! The evaluation of the engines are very misleading in this
type of positions. They usually give White at least 0.6 advantage, but it is
hard for White to make any progress on the queenside, while Black's
counterplay on the kingside is coming slowly, but has good punching power.} (
13... Bf8 {is transposing to 12... Bf8 but there is no need to defend d6 in
this way anymore.}) 14. Nd2 Rf8 15. Bb2 Ne8 16. Nb5 f5 17. exf5 gxf5 (17...
Nxf5 $5 {also looks fully playable for Black}) 18. f4 Ng6 19. fxe5 Nxe5 20. Ra3
Bd7 21. Qa1 Qe7 {With unclear play. Black went on to win a good game in
Eljanov-Hjartarson, Reykjavik 2018}) 13... Nxc6 14. Bxd6 {[%csl Rd4] Black has
some compensation: there is the hole on d4 and Black has active pieces. But
overall White should be able to keep an advantage.} Nd4 (14... Bg4 15. c5 $14)
15. c5 b6 {undermining the powerful bishop on d6.} ({The alternative} 15... Qa5
{can be answered with} 16. Nxd4 $1 exd4 17. Nd5 Nxe4 (17... Nxd5 18. exd5 Bd7
19. Ra2 $1 $16 {when the a4 pawn is taboo because after} Bxa4 20. Qd3 {[%cal
Rf1a1] Black is tied up on the a-file.}) 18. Bb5 Be6 19. Nc7 Red8 20. Nxa8 Nxd6
21. cxd6 Rxd6 22. Qf3 Qxa8 23. Rac1 $14 {It is hard to say how good White's
winning chances are in this position, but it is clear that White will be
playing for two results.}) 16. Bb5 Bd7 17. Bxd7 Nxd7 18. Nd5 Rc8 19. cxb6 Nxb6
20. Bc7 Rxc7 21. Nxb6 $14) (12... b6 {transposes to the mainline}) (12... Bg4
$6 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 {is not a very good exchange for Black. After} Bf8 {
Brouwer-De Jong, Leiden 2018} 15. Qc2 {White is clearly better}) 13. Re1 {
I think this is a beneficial move in general. It also serves a bit as a
waiting move.} ({This time the advance} 13. c5 $2 {is refuted by} dxc5 14. Bxc5
Nexd5) 13... c5 14. Ba3 Nd7 (14... Bh6 $5 {stopping Bc1 is a smart idea. White
could try} 15. Bf1 Rf8 {[%cal Yf7f5] Black is preparing the ... f7-f5 break}
16. Nb5 Nh5 {and now there is the typical piece sacrifice} 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18.
Bxc5 $44) {In this position I think White should spend some time to make ...
f7-f5 unattractive, and only later concentrate on the queenside:} 15. Nb5 Ra6 {
and now I believe White should play} 16. Bc1 $1 Bg7 17. Bd3 h6 (17... f5 {
[%csl Re6] looks premature when White has a knight on f3. There will follow}
18. Ng5 Nf6 19. exf5 Nxf5 (19... gxf5 20. Ra3 $1 {[%cal Rg3h3,Ra3h3] The rook
is well placed on the 3rd rank. It sometimes can switch to the kingside to
help in an attack against the enemy king!}) 20. Ra3 {and now after} h6 21. Ne6
Bxe6 22. dxe6 Rxe6 23. g4 $1 Ne7 24. h4 {Promises White excellent play for the
sacrificed pawn.}) 18. Ra3 f5 $2 {This is normally Black's number one plan,
but it should be carefully prepared.} (18... Rf8 19. Nh4 Nxd5 $2 ({even here} 
19... f5 {runs into all kind of trouble after} 20. exf5 gxf5 21. Bc2 $16) 20.
Nxg6) 19. exf5 gxf5 20. Nh4 Nf6 21. Qc2 $16 {Black's pawns on e5 and f5 make a
strong impression, but as soon as one of the pawns move forward they lose
their flexibility and new weaknesses appear.} e4 (21... f4 22. g3 $1 {[%cal
Rb1h7]}) 22. Be2 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Ga3g3] White has a large advantage} *

