1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5 10. Ba3 axb4 (10... Nd7 11. bxa5 Rxa5 12. Bb4 Ra8 13. a4 {is
another move order that has been used to get to the same position.}) 11. Bxb4
Nd7 {With this move Black prepares to advance ...f7-f5 and to stop White's
c4-c5 break. It used to be a trend line, as my database returns over 1000
games with this position. Still, I have the feeling that King's Indian players
have been looking more at other ways of handling the Bayonet attack.} 12. a4 {
Now Black can choose from a large number of options. The most popular by far
is 12...Bh6 but we will also analyze in depth the alternatives.} Bh6 (12... f5
$6 {This looks a bit too primitive to me, as White has the thematic reply} 13.
Ng5 Nc5 (13... Nf6 {has also been tried here, but this looks very suspicious
to me as White's play seems to be much faster after} 14. c5 fxe4 15. cxd6 cxd6
16. Ngxe4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Rf4 (17... Nf5 18. Bg4 {also doesn't look like a lot
of fun for Black}) 18. Bf3 Bf5 19. Qd3 {and I see nothing better for Black
than to continue} Bxe4 20. Bxe4 Rf7 21. a5 $1 $16) 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. a5 (15.
Bf3 {was played in a blitz encounter between Kramnik and Kasparov. White got a
promising endgame after} Ra6 $6 (15... Bf6 $1 {looks like a better try.}) 16.
a5 Kh8 $2 17. Ne6 Bxe6 18. dxe6 f4 19. Qxd8 Rxd8 20. Rfb1 Rb8 21. Nd5 $16 {
Kramnik-Kasparov, Moscow blitz 1998}) 15... Ra6 16. Qb3 Bf6 17. Ne6 Bxe6 18.
dxe6 Qc8 19. Nd5 {with a clear advantage to White.}) (12... h6 {[%cal Gf7f5]
prepares the move ...f7-f5 without allowing any Ng5 jumps. This is too slow,
as is illustrated by the following lines:} 13. Nd2 (13. a5 f5 {transposes after
} 14. Nd2) 13... f5 14. a5 Nf6 (14... Kh8 15. f3 h5 {[%cal Gg7h6,Gh6e3] is
another typical King's Indian plan. Black tries to activate his dark-squared
bishop to the a7-g1 diagonal by Bh6-e3. White obviously should prevent that.
The best way to do so is with} 16. Nb3 Bh6 17. Qd3 {[%cal Gc4c5] and White is
ready to push c5.}) 15. c5 Ne8 16. f3 {and to me this seems like a dream
King's Indian as Black's attack is very far away.}) (12... Nc5 13. a5 (13. Bxc5
dxc5 14. a5 b6 (14... Bd7 15. Qb3 Ra7) 15. axb6 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 cxb6 17. Rb1 Bd7
18. Qa6 Nc8 19. Qb7) 13... Bd7 $2 (13... Na6 14. Ba3) (13... f5 14. Bxc5 dxc5
15. Ng5 Bh6 16. Ne6 Bxe6 17. dxe6 Bd2 18. Nd5 Bxa5 19. Qb3 c6 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7
21. exf5 Rxf5 (21... gxf5 22. Qg3+ Kh8 23. Qxe5+ Qg7 24. Qxg7+ Kxg7 25. Rfd1
$14) 22. Rfd1 $44) 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Qb3 Ra7 16. a6 $5 Rxa6 17. Rxa6 bxa6 18.
Qa3 f5 19. Re1 $1 fxe4 20. Nxe4 Nf5 21. Nxc5 $16 {Lautier-Novik, Dubai 2002}) (
12... Kh8 $5 {is one of the recommendations of Bologan in his 2017 book
'Bologan's King's Indian'. Can Black afford to make waiting moves here?} 13. a5
f5 14. Bd3 $146 {White is continuing as normal in the mainline.} ({This move
is better than} 14. Ng5 Nb8 $1 {as pointed out by Bologan when Black is close
to setting up a blockade on the queenside with ...Na6.}) 14... Nf6 (14... Bh6
15. Re1 {transposes to 12...Bh6 13.a5 f5 14.Bd3 Kh8}) 15. c5 fxe4 16. cxd6 cxd6
17. Nxe4 {and the following lines are good to memorize when you want to play
this line because it is very concrete:} Bg4 (17... Nfxd5 18. Bxd6 Bg4 19. Bc4
$1 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Nf4 21. Kh1 $16) 18. Bxd6 $1 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Nxe4 20. Bxe7 Qxe7
21. Bxe4 {with a sharp position where Black has some compensation for the pawn,
but still White's chances should be rated higher.}) (12... b6 {This move is
not very logical. Better to play 11...b6 in that case. With the knight on d7
black does not threaten to play ...c7-c5.}) (12... Re8 {[%cal Gg7f8] with the
idea ...Bf8 is a very rare move here, but the idea starts to gain popularity
in slightly different positions. The simplest way to achieve an advantage is
with} 13. a5 (13. Nd2) 13... c5 14. dxc6 Nxc6 15. Bxd6 Rxa5 16. Rxa5 Qxa5 (
16... Nxa5 $4 17. Nd5) 17. Nd5 {When White has the more active position.}) 13.
a5 $1 f5 14. Bd3 (14. Nd2) 14... Kh8 $6 {I am not sure what this move is
trying to achieve. To me, it seems that the insertion of the moves ...Kh8 and
Re1 are in White's favor. Still, this has been the most popular way for Black
to handle this position.} ({Black has also tried the immediate} 14... Nf6 15.
c5 fxe4 16. Nxe4 (16. cxd6) 16... Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Bf5 (17... Rf4 18. cxd6 cxd6
19. Qd3 Bf5 20. Nd2 $14) (17... Nf5 18. Re1 $14) 18. Re1 Qd7 (18... Bxe4 $6 19.
Rxe4 Rf4 {is met with a simple refutation. White goes} 20. Rxf4 Bxf4 21. Qb3
Nf5 {and now} 22. Re1 $16 {just stops all counterplay, after which White can
concentrate his efforts on the queenside with moves like Bc3}) 19. Rb1 {
Continuing in the style of Kramnik-Carlsen is equally effective here.} (19. Qb3
$5 Qb5 (19... Bxe4 20. Rxe4 Bg7 21. Bc3 $14) 20. cxd6 cxd6 21. Rab1 Bxe4 22.
Rxe4 Nf5 (22... Nxd5 $2 23. Bxd6 Qxb3 24. Rxb3 Rf7 25. Rxe5 Rxa5 26. Re8+ Bf8
27. g3 $16)) 19... Bxe4 (19... Kh8 $6 {for tactical reasons the king is badly
placed here.} 20. Bc3 Ra7 {was seen in Lautier-Roeder, Bundesliga 2001. Now
White can strike with} 21. Rxb7 $1 Rxb7 22. c6 Qc8 23. cxb7 Qxb7 24. Nxe5 $1 {
and White wins material in all the lines, e.g.} Bg7 (24... dxe5 25. Bxe5+ Kg8
26. d6 Bxe4 27. dxe7 Re8 28. Rxe4 $1 Qxe4 29. Qb3+) 25. Qa1 dxe5 (25... Bxe4
26. Nxg6+) 26. Bxe5 Bxe5 27. Qxe5+ Kg8 28. Qxe7 $18) 20. Rxe4 Qf5 ({or} 20...
Rfd8 21. Be1 Qf5 22. Qd3 $14) 21. cxd6 cxd6 {and now White has everything
under control after} 22. Qd3) (14... Rf7 {This move has been tried 6 times,
but White won all games. Still, we should have a little look at it, as it was
played by strong players like Morozevich and Piket. I propose to continue as
we do against ... Kh8} 15. Re1 (15. h4 $5 Nf6 16. Ng5 Rf8 (16... Bxg5 17. hxg5
Nxe4 18. Bxe4 fxe4 19. Nxe4 $14) 17. c5 fxe4 18. Bxe4 $14) 15... Nf6 16. c5
fxe4 17. Nxe4 {and here Morozevich blundered} Nexd5 $2 {against one of the
biggest experts of the Bayonet line, GM Loek van Wely.} (17... Nxe4 18. Bxe4 {
is similar to the 14...Kh8 lines. The rook on f7 is defending in advance the
b7 pawn but the character of the position is the same with White enjoying a
solid advantage.}) {There followed} 18. Bc4 $1 Nxb4 19. cxd6 {and Black is
losing material.} Nfd5 ({unpinning with} 19... Kg7 {also results in material
losses after} 20. Bxf7 Kxf7 21. Nxe5+ Kg7 22. Nxf6 Qxf6 23. d7) (19... Nxe4 20.
Nxe5 $18) 20. Bxd5 Nxd5 21. Qxd5 c6 22. Qb3 Rxa5 23. Rxa5 Qxa5 24. d7 Bxd7 25.
Nd6 Qd5 26. Qxd5 cxd5 27. Nxf7 Kxf7 28. Nxe5+ {and White went on to win in Van
Wely-Morozevich, Monte Carlo 2007}) 15. Re1 Nf6 (15... Ng8 16. h3 Ndf6 17. c5 (
17. exf5 $5 gxf5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Bxf8 Qxf8 20. Rxe5 $14) 17... fxe4 18. Bxe4
Rf7 (18... Nxe4 19. Nxe4 Ra6 $8 20. cxd6 cxd6 21. Qb3 Nf6 22. Nxd6 $1 Rxd6 23.
Nxe5 $16 Rxd5 $2 (23... Nh5 24. Rad1 Nf4 25. Bxd6 Qxd6 26. Qb6 Qxb6 27. axb6
$16) 24. Be7 $1 $18) 19. Bc2 Bf5 20. Bb3 Ne8 21. c6 (21. Qe2 $1 Ngf6 22. Qc4)
21... Qb8 22. g4 bxc6 23. dxc6 Bc2 24. Bxc2 Qxb4 25. Nd5 Qc5 {Smirnov-Jenni,
Istanbul 2004} (25... Qb5 26. g5 $5 Bg7 27. Nh4) 26. a6 $14) 16. c5 fxe4 17.
cxd6 {White chooses to release the tension in the centre.} (17. Nxe4 $2 {
can be well met with} Nexd5 {now Black's king has left the a2-g8 diagonal.})
17... cxd6 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 (18... Nexd5 $5 19. Bxd6 (19. Ba3 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Nc3
21. Qxd6 Rxa5 $1 $13) 19... Nxe4 20. Bxf8 $1 (20. Bxe4 Qxd6 21. Qxd5 $14) 20...
Nec3 (20... Nxf2 21. Kxf2 Qxf8 22. Kg1 Ne3 23. Qb3 Qc5 24. Kh1 Ng4 25. Re2 $16
Nf2+ $2 26. Rxf2 Qxf2 27. Qd5 $18) (20... Ndc3 $2 21. Qc2 Qxf8 22. Bxe4 $18)
21. Bxh6 Nxd1 22. Raxd1 $18) 19. Bxe4 Bf5 20. Rb1 {Not the most popular move
in this position, but it was Kramnik's choice in a game against Carlsen. With
his last move White improves his position, and it seems that there is no real
counterplay for Black. Carlsen continued with} Qd7 21. h3 Rac8 22. Qb3 Rf7 {
and here, instead of Kramnik's 23.Bc3 we can improve White's play with} 23. Ba3
$1 {Sipke Ernst: '+/ -!'} (23. Qa3 $5) (23. Bc3 $2 Bxe4 24. Rxe4 Qf5 $13 {
Kramnik-Carlsen, Monaco 2009}) 23... Bxe4 (23... Rb8 24. a6 {looks already
hopeless for Black}) 24. Rxe4 Nf5 (24... Rb8 25. Rb4 Nc8 26. a6 b6 27. Rh4 {
and my engine thinks White has a +4 advantage!}) 25. Rxe5 $1 Nh4 (25... dxe5 {
also leads to a poor endgame more or less by force:} 26. Nxe5 Qe8 27. Nxf7+
Qxf7 28. g4 $1 Nd4 29. Qxb7 Qxb7 30. Rxb7 Ra8 31. a6 Rxa6 32. Rb8+ Kg7 33. Bf8+
) 26. Re6 Nxf3+ 27. gxf3 $16 *

