1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5 10. Ba3 axb4 11. Bxb4 b6 12. a4 Re8 $5 {This move has been known
for quite some time but recently it has increased in popularity because of a
new idea for Black.} (12... Ne8 {is almost equally popular, but I am not
convinced that e8 is the right square for the knight. Play can continue as
follows:} 13. Qb3 $1 ({Still many games continued} 13. a5 $2 {when after} c5 $1
14. dxc6 Nxc6 15. Ba3 Rxa5 16. Nb5 {White is probably equalizing, but
definitely not more.}) 13... Rb8 (13... Kh8 $5 {A typical King's Indian
waiting move. The king is safer in the corner now as White has placed the
queen on the a2-g8 diagonal.} 14. Nb5 (14. a5 c5 15. dxc6 Nxc6 (15... bxa5 16.
c7 Qxc7 17. Nb5 Qc6 18. Qa3 Ra6 19. Bxa5 Qa8 (19... Qxe4 $15) 20. Nd2 $2 (20.
c5 $1 dxc5 21. Qxc5 Rxa5 22. Rxa5 Qxa5 23. Qxe7 Ba6 24. Qa7 $14) 20... Nc6 21.
Nb3 Nxa5 22. Nxa5 Qxe4 $15 {Gyimesi-Vajda, Hungary 2005} (22... Bf6 $5)) 16.
axb6 Rxa1 17. Rxa1 Qxb6 18. Nb5 Nxb4 19. Qxb4 f5 $13) 14... f5 15. Nd2) (13...
c5 14. dxc6 Nxc6 15. Rfd1 $14) 14. Nb5 f5 15. Nd2 (15. a5) 15... Bh6 16. a5 (
16. Qd3) 16... bxa5 17. Bxa5 Bxd2 18. Bxd2 fxe4 (18... Nf6 19. Bh6 Re8 20. f3
$16) 19. c5 $5 (19. Qc2 $44) (19. Bg5 $44) 19... Nf5 (19... Nf6 20. Ba5 Nf5 21.
Qa2 Rf7 22. Rac1 Ne8 23. cxd6 Nfxd6 24. Nxd6 Qxd6 25. Rc6 $14) 20. Qc4 dxc5 $1
(20... Kh8 $2 21. Ra7 $16 c6 {Sokolov-Reinderman, Netherlands 1996} 22. dxc6 $1
Rxb5 (22... d5 23. Qa2 $18) 23. Rf7 $3 Nc7 (23... Rxf7 $2 24. Qxf7 $18) (23...
Nf6 24. c7 Qe8 25. Rxf8+ Qxf8 26. Qxb5 Nd4 27. Qa6 $3 $18) (23... Rg8 24. Qxb5
Nd4 25. Qb8 Nxe2+ 26. Kh1 $18 {Markos}) 24. Bg5 $1 Be6 25. Bxd8 Rxf7 26. cxd6
Bxc4 27. dxc7 Rxc7 28. Bxc4 Rc5 29. Bxc7 Rxc4 30. Bxe5+ Kg8 31. c7 $18) 21. d6+
Kh8 (21... Rf7 $2 22. dxc7 Nxc7 23. Ba5 Be6 24. Bxc7 $1 Bxc4 25. Bxc4 Qf8 26.
Bxb8 Qxb8 27. Ra7 Nh6 (27... Nd6 28. Nxd6 Qxa7 29. Nxf7 $16) 28. Rd1 e3 $1 (
28... Kg7 29. Bxf7 Nxf7 30. Rdd7 Qxb5 31. Rxf7+ Kh6 (31... Kg8 $2 32. Rfb7 Qe8
33. Rg7+ Kf8 34. Rxh7 $18) 32. h4 Kh5 (32... g5 33. Rxh7+ Kg6 34. g4 gxh4 35.
Rag7+ Kf6 36. Rb7 Qa5 37. Rb6+ $18) 33. Rxh7+ Kg4 34. Kh2 $16) 29. fxe3 Kg7 30.
Rxf7+ (30. Bxf7 Nxf7 31. Rdd7 Qxb5 32. Rxf7+ Kh6 33. h4 Kh5 34. Rxh7+ Kg4 35.
Kh2 c4 $13) 30... Nxf7 31. Rd7 Kh6 32. Rxf7 $16) 22. Ba5 (22. dxc7 Nxc7 23.
Qxc5 Rxb5 (23... Nxb5 $2 24. Qxe5+ $18) 24. Bxb5 Nxb5 25. Qxe5+ Kg8 26. Qxb5
Qxd2 27. Qc4+ Kh8 28. Qxe4 $13) 22... Rxb5 (22... Nexd6 23. Qxc5 Nxb5 24. Bxb5
$14) 23. Qxb5 Qxd6 $13) (12... Nh5 13. a5 ({White has also had succes with} 13.
Re1 f5 (13... Nf4 14. Bf1 f5 {, but the text move is more straightforward.}))
13... bxa5 (13... Ba6 $2 {was played in a couple of games, but the bishop is
entirely misplaced after} 14. axb6 cxb6 15. g3 $16) (13... f5 $2 {just loses
here to} 14. axb6 Rxa1 15. Qxa1 fxe4 16. Nxe4 Nf4 17. Bd1 {Xu-Serrano Alvarez,
2003}) 14. Bxa5 Nf4 ({It is good to be aware of the following trick:} 14... h6
$2 {loses to} 15. Bxc7 $1 Rxa1 16. Bxd8 Rxd1 17. Bxe7 Rxf1+ 18. Bxf1) (14...
Ba6 $2 {is a way to stop Nb5 ideas, but looks just wrong.} 15. Re1 {looks best
to me, when there could follow} Bh6 16. c5 Bxe2 17. Rxe2 Nf4 18. Rea2 {with a
large advantage}) (14... Bd7 $2 {is also a blunder, as White can go} 15. c5
dxc5 16. d6) 15. Nd2 Qd7 (15... f5 16. Re1 fxe4 17. Ncxe4 Nf5 18. Bf1 Nd4 19.
Bc3 Rxa1 20. Bxa1 {The Black knights look impressive, but White has everything
under control. White can now challenge the knight on d4 and later on think
about pushing c4-c5.} Re8 {This move anticipates the opening of the e-file.
This position was reached in Capak-Nalepovic, 2004. Here White could have
continued with} (20... Bf5 21. g3 Nh3+ 22. Bxh3 Bxh3 23. Bxd4 exd4 24. Nb3 {
and White takes d4.}) (20... Qh4 {is probably best, but here I recommend} 21.
Qa4 $1 {when c7 is vulnerable and Black has no tactics against the White king.}
(21. Bc3 $5 {is also worth looking into.})) 21. h4 $1 $146 Qxh4 $2 (21... Bf5
22. g3 Nh5 23. Bxd4 exd4 24. Ng5 $14) 22. Bxd4 exd4 23. Nf6+) 16. Re1 Bh6 {
This move was played in the stem game between Anand and Polgar.} ({In future
games Black chose to take the bishop:} 16... Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2 c6 (17... f5 {
should be met with the immediate} 18. c5 $1 Ba6 (18... dxc5 19. Nb3 $16) 19. c6
Qc8 20. Qd1 {When in the long run White's advanced c-pawn is a great asset.})
18. Reb1 cxd5 19. cxd5 Ba6 20. Qe3 {[%csl Rd6] was a game between Xu and Li,
2017. White has a pleasant albeit small advantage.}) 17. Bf1 c6 $2 (17... c5
18. Nb5) 18. c5 $1 cxd5 19. exd5 dxc5 20. Nde4 Bg7 {Anand-Polgar, Dos Hermanas
1997, and here White could have secured a large advantage with} 21. Nxc5 $16)
(12... Nd7 {Transposes to the file 11...Nd7}) 13. Qd3 {White needs to find a
way to prepare a5 without allowing ...c7-c5. From this square, the queen
retains the pressure on d6.} ({The idea behind 12...Re8 is that if White goes
immediately} 13. a5 {Black can respond with} c5 $1 14. dxc6 Nxc6 15. Bxd6 Rxa5
{or 15...Nd4!? and this type of position is usually quite ok for Black.}) 13...
Nf5 $5 {This flashy move is one of the main points behind 11....Re8} (13... Nd7
{has been tried as well, but I think White keeps an edge after} 14. a5 c5 (
14... bxa5 15. Bxa5 $36 {[%csl Rc7]}) 15. dxc6 Nxc6 16. Bxd6 Rxa5 17. Rxa5 Nxa5
{Bromberger-Golubev, 1999} 18. Rd1 $1 $146 Nb7 19. Ba3 Nbc5 20. Qe3 {[%cal
Gc3d5] followed by 21.Nd5}) (13... Nh5 $6 14. g3 f5 {was also tried in a
couple of games, but with the rook on e8 this doesn't seem to make a lot of
sense to me. White's play on the queenside is quite straightforward:} 15. a5
bxa5 16. Bxa5 {(threatening 17.Bxc7)} fxe4 17. Nxe4 Bf5 18. Nfd2 (18. Nfg5 $5)
18... Qd7 {Rogozenco-Djukic, 2002} 19. c5 $5 {and if} dxc5 20. d6 cxd6 21. Qxd6
$36) 14. a5 (14. exf5 $6 e4 15. Qd2 exf3 16. Bxf3 Bxf5 {and it is White who
has to be careful}) 14... bxa5 15. Rxa5 ({It is also interesting to investigate
} 15. Bxa5 Bd7 (15... Ba6 {could be a better move for Black, although it still
is not clear to me how Black fully equalizes after} 16. Rfb1 Nd4 17. Bf1) 16.
exf5 e4 17. Qd2 exf3 18. Bxf3 Ra7 (18... Bxf5 19. Nb5 $16) 19. fxg6 hxg6 20.
Ra3) 15... Rb8 16. Nb5 Nd4 17. Nfxd4 exd4 18. f3 Nh5 (18... Nd7 19. Qd2 (19.
Ra7 Ne5 20. Qd1 $1)) (18... Bd7 {was tried in one game.} 19. Rf2 $5 ({The
obvious looking} 19. Ra7 {was played in Hilverda-Ratsma, 2016, but this allows
Black to equalize with the following tactic:} Nxd5 $1 20. exd5 Bf5 21. Qd2 d3
22. Bxd3 Rxb5 23. cxb5 (23. Bxf5 $2 Rxb4 24. Qxb4 Bd4+ 25. Kh1 Bxa7 $15) 23...
Bd4+ 24. Kh1 Bxd3) 19... Bxb5 20. cxb5 Nd7 21. Qc2 {with the better chances})
19. Bd2 ({I prefer the texmove over} 19. g3 Bh3 20. Re1 {as Black obtains
counterplay with} f5 $1 {as was seen in Bacrot-Parvanyan, Bundesliga 2018})
19... Qh4 {[%cal Gg7e5]} (19... f5 20. Nxd4 Qh4 21. f4 {transposes}) 20. f4 {
This move is necessary as Black was threatening 20...Be5} f5 21. Nxd4 Rb2 (
21... Bxd4+ 22. Qxd4 Rxe4 23. Qa7 Rb7 24. Qa8 Qd8 25. Bxh5 gxh5 26. Ra3 {
and I think this position with opposite coloured bishops is very hard for Black
}) ({a better try is} 21... fxe4 22. Qe3 Bg4 {although I still like White after
} 23. Bxg4 Qxg4 24. Ne6) 22. Bxh5 $1 Qxh5 23. Bc3 Rb7 24. Ra8 fxe4 25. Qe3 $16
{Kotanjian-Petrosian, 2010. Black has no counterplay.} *

