1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Rf7f5] You could call this the old mainline. In
my database, it is still almost 3 times as popular as any other move for Black
on the move 9 but if you look at all the games from last year, the picture
changes dramatically. I don't think that it is because of the quality of the
move that 9...Nh5 is dropping in popularity, it is just not a very practical
decision to have it in your repertoire. There are too many ways for White to
play against this line and Black has to be prepared for all of them. Therefore
it is a huge shortcut to go for 9...a5 instead.} 10. g3 $5 {[%csl Gf4,Rg2,Rh3]
I have chosen this move as it looks to me to be the most interesting. The
mainline continues with 10.Re1, but I think this line has already been
analyzed so well that it is difficult to come up with any new ideas that will
shake the evaluation of the line. Of course to play 10.g3 is a bit
double-edged, because yes, we are now controlling the f4-square, but the
downside is that our kingside is now slightly weakened. The move has many
followers though, and most notably Kramnik, Gelfand and Van Wely helped to
advance this line.} f5 {The mainline, and also the repertoire suggestion by
Kornev in his recent book on the King's Indian.} ({it is interesting to see
whether the inclusion of 9...Nh5 10.g3 makes} 10... a5 {a better move. This
time I think White should go} 11. bxa5 Rxa5 (11... c5 $2 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. Nb3 {
just drops a pawn. The extra pawn might not seem very important, but in the
future White can prepare to sacrifice a piece on c5 and it is important that
Black cannot defend against it with ...b7-b6.}) 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. Nb3 Ra8 14. c5
{White managed to carry out the desired advance. True, the knight on b3 looks
a little misplaced but White's chances should still be rated a little higher.})
(10... h6 11. Nd2) (10... c6 11. dxc6 Nxc6 12. Rb1 {is my recommendation} ({
but it is also possible to look into} 12. Nb5 Nxb4 13. Nxd6 Qc7 14. c5 b6 (
14... Qxc5 15. Be3 Qc7 16. Rc1 Nc6 17. Ng5 $14) (14... Bh3 {and here White
should boldly sacrifice an exchange with} 15. Be3 $1 Bxf1 16. Bxf1 b6 17. Bc4
$14) 15. Be3 bxc5 16. a3 Nc6 17. Bxc5 Rd8 18. Rc1 Bh6 19. Rc3 $16 {
Walczak-Shadrin, corr. 2006}) 12... Nf6 13. Qd3 {White can slowly build up his
position whereas for Black it is difficult to find any counterplay.} Re8 14.
Be3 Ng4 15. b5 Na5 (15... Nxe3 $2 16. bxc6 {loses material}) 16. Bg5 f6 17. Bc1
$14 {Van Wely-Shchekachev, France 2000}) (10... Kh8 {can be met with} 11. Nd2
$1) 11. Ng5 {[%csl Ge6] The knight is jumping towards the e6-square, where it
will exchange itself for the Bc8.} Nf6 ({Forcing the exchange immediately was
tried a couple of times but likely transposes after} 11... h6 12. Ne6 Bxe6 13.
dxe6 Nf6 ({There is also the hardly tried and suspicious looking} 13... fxe4 {
when White should continue} 14. Bxh5 gxh5 15. Qxh5 Nf5 16. Nd5 c6 (16... Qe8
17. Qg4 Rc8 18. e7 Rf7 (18... Nxe7 $4 19. Qe6+ {loses a piece}) 19. f4 $1 $14)
17. g4 $1 Ne7 18. Nc3 $14) 14. f3) 12. f3 f4 $5 {A serious move, and the
mainline in Kotronias' series on the King's Indian.} (12... h6 {is also
playable, but it does lead to positions where White gets to sacrifice a pawn
for enough compensation, and maybe even a bit more than that.} 13. Ne6 Bxe6 14.
dxe6 c6 15. Be3 ({In the stem-game between Taimanov and Gligoric, White
continued} 15. b5 Qc7 16. Rb1 Rfd8 17. Qa4 Qc8 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. Be3 Qxe6 {
Black is now a pawn up, but White has two bishops and also gets a rook to the
7th rank.} 20. Rb7 a5 21. Rfb1 f4 22. Bf2 h5 $6 {Taimanov-Gligoric, Santa Fe
1960} (22... Kh8 $1 {side-stepping tricks on the a2-g8 diagonal were called
for.}) 23. c5 d5 24. exd5 Nexd5 (24... cxd5 $2 25. R1b6 $18) 25. Bc4 {Gives
White more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 15... Qc7 {Black prepares
to take the e6-pawn with the queen, but first needs to support the d6-pawn
with a rook.} (15... f4 16. Bf2 Qc7 17. b5 Rfd8 18. Rb1 Qc8 19. Qa4 Qxe6 (19...
fxg3 20. hxg3 c5 21. Nd5 Qxe6 22. Nc7 Qh3 23. g4 Rac8 24. Rb3 Nh5 25. f4 Qxb3
26. axb3 Nxf4 27. Ne6 Nxe2+ 28. Kg2 Nf4+ 29. Nxf4 exf4 30. Qxa7 Rd7 31. Rd1 $14
{Ghiani-Bobel, corr. 2010}) 20. bxc6 bxc6 21. Rb7 a5 22. Rfb1) ({Breaking open
the centre with} 15... d5 $2 {backfires: After} 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Nxd5 Nfxd5
18. exd5 Qxd5 (18... Nxd5 19. Qb3 $18 {is even worse}) 19. Qxd5 Nxd5 20. Bc5
Rfc8 21. e7 $16 {Van Wely-Warmerdam, Dutch league 2016. Black probably has to
give up an exchange.}) 16. Qd2 ({In another classic battle White continued} 16.
Qb3 Rad8 17. Rad1 Qc8 18. Bxa7 Qxe6 19. Bb6 Rd7 {Szabo-Gligoric, Buenos Aires
1960}) 16... Kh7 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 18. b5 Qc8 19. Rab1 Qxe6 20. bxc6 bxc6 21. Rb7
d5 22. Bc5 Neg8 23. cxd5 cxd5 24. exf5 Qxf5 25. Nb5 a6 26. Nc7 Qc8 27. Rdb1 $13
{The position remains complicated, but I prefer White as the initiative is on
his side.}) (12... c6 {This move is given as interesting by Bologan in his
most recent book on the King's Indian.} 13. Be3 f4 ({Bologan gives the
following line} 13... Bh6 14. Kh1 {and continues with} Nfxd5 $1 15. cxd5 f4 16.
gxf4 exf4 17. dxc6 Bxg5 18. cxb7 Bxb7 19. Bd4 Bf6 {as was seen in the game
Nikolov-Kr. Georgiev, Bulgaria 1988. Bologan concludes that this is a
defendable position, but the engines disagree. After} 20. Rc1 {White is just
much better.}) 14. Bf2 Bh6 (14... Ne8 15. c5 cxd5 16. exd5 Nf5 17. Ne6 Bxe6 18.
dxe6 fxg3 19. hxg3 Nd4 20. Bc4 Kh8 21. Bxd4 exd4 22. Nd5 $14 {Van Wely-Valvo,
Newark 1995}) 15. Ne6 Bxe6 16. dxe6 fxg3 17. hxg3 Qc7 (17... Ne8 18. Qb3 Nc7
19. Rad1 Kh8 20. c5 d5 21. exd5 Nexd5 {Nielsen-Socko, Helsingor 2008} 22. Kg2
Qf6 23. Rh1 Bg7 24. Ne4 $16) 18. Kg2 Rad8 19. Rh1 Kg7 20. Qc2 Qc8 21. Bxa7 Qxe6
22. Bf2 $14) 13. b5 $1 ({There is another interesting choice for White here:} 
13. Kg2 $5) 13... fxg3 {This is the start of a long forced sequence.} (13... h6
14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. dxe6 fxg3 16. hxg3 {transposes to 13... fxg3}) (13... Ne8 $5
14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. dxe6 c5 16. Nd5 Nc7 17. Nxc7 Qxc7 $11 {Bacrot-Onischuk,
Yerevan 2014}) 14. hxg3 h6 (14... Nh5 15. Kf2 h6 (15... Nf4 $6 16. gxf4 exf4
17. Qd3 h6 (17... Nc6 18. bxc6 Qxg5 19. Ke1 bxc6 20. dxc6 Bh3 21. Rh1 Qg2 22.
Rxh3 $1 Qxh3 23. Rb1 Rab8 24. Rb7 $1 $16 {Marquardt-Vanchak, corr. 2010}) 18.
Ne6 Bxe6 19. dxe6 $16 {Van Wely-Dyachkov, Dagomys 2008}) 16. Ne6 Bxe6 17. dxe6
Qc8 18. c5 Qxe6 19. Qb3 Qxb3 20. axb3 dxc5 21. Ba3 $1 b6 (21... Rfd8 22. Bxc5
Bf8 23. Be3 $44 {Iturriziga-Stets, 2015}) 22. b4 c4 (22... cxb4 $6 23. Bxb4
Rfe8 24. Bc4+ Kh8 25. Nd5 c5 26. Bc3 Nxd5 27. Bxd5 Rad8 28. Rxa7 Nf6 29. Bc4
$16) 23. Bxc4+ Kh7 24. Bc1 Nf6 25. Kg2 Rfd8 26. Be3 $14) 15. Ne6 Bxe6 16. dxe6
Qc8 17. Nd5 Qxe6 18. Nxc7 Qh3 19. Rf2 $1 {Still over 30 games have been played
with this position.} Rac8 (19... Nxe4 20. Rh2 $1 ({The following line is given
by Bologan in his recent book 'Bologan's King's Indian', published in 2017:} 
20. fxe4 $1 Rxf2 21. Kxf2 Rf8+ 22. Ke3 Qxg3+ 23. Kd2 Rf2 24. Ne8 {and he
argues that White has an advantage after 24.. .h5, as was played in Van
Wely-Radjabov, Dresden 2008, a game that Van Wely went on to win. However
Black has the strong resource} Qf3 $3 25. Nxd6 Bf6 {as was already seen in the
game Van Wely-Stellwagen, Dutch league 2009. White quickly ended up in trouble
and lost.}) 20... Qd7 (20... Qxg3+ $2 21. Rg2 Nc3 22. Rxg3 Nxd1 23. Bxd1 Rac8
24. Nd5 Nxd5 25. cxd5 $16) 21. fxe4 Qxc7 22. Be3 Kh7 23. Qd2 Ng8 24. g4 $14 {
Haugen-Dosi, corr. 2009}) 20. Rh2 Qxg3+ (20... Qd7 $2 {is too passive and
allows White to get the upper hand with} 21. b6 axb6 (21... Nh5 $2 {allowed}
22. c5 $1 {[%cal Ra2g8] when White has many threats. After} axb6 23. cxd6 Rxc7
24. dxc7 Qxc7 25. Rg2 $18 {Sadzikowski-Gaehwiler, Caldas Novas 2011}) 22. Nb5
Nh5 23. Kg2 Rf6 24. Ba3 Nc6 25. Bxd6 $16) 21. Rg2 Qh3 22. Qxd6 Rf7 23. c5 $1 {
With this move White creates the strong threat of Bc4.} ({Kotronias gives} 23.
Qe6 {but concludes that after} Qh4 {Black holds the balance. Still, resources
are far from exhausted here as well.}) 23... Nf5 $1 {This is the only way for
Black to stay in the game.} (23... Nxe4 $2 {doesn't work because of} 24. fxe4
Qc3 25. Bb2 $1 Qxb2 26. Rd1 Qc3 27. Kh2 $16) ({In the stem game Black continued
} 23... Bf8 $2 {but quickly found himself in a lost position after} 24. Ne6
Nxe4 25. Qxe5 Nc3 26. Bc4 $18 {Van Wely-Golubev, Sovata 2000}) 24. exf5 Rfxc7 {
This is a critical position, and here I left my engine running for quite a
while.} 25. Be3 $1 {was the choice of Giri, and it is the most tricky move.} ({
initially, the engines go for} 25. c6 {but it appears that after} Qxf5 26. Bc4+
Kh7 27. Be6 Qxf3 28. Bxc8 Rxc8 29. Bd2 $1 Bf8 $3 {Black is forcing a draw.
Kotronias analyzed this line, and it appeared in Zmokly-Efendiyev, Corr 2010})
25... Kh8 (25... Qxf5 $2 26. Rf1 {gives White a great initiative for the pawn.
After} Bf8 27. Bd3 $1 e4 28. fxe4 Qxf1+ 29. Bxf1 Bxd6 30. cxd6 $16 {
Giri-Bacrot, Biel 2012 Black's position is on the verge of collapsing.}) 26.
Bxh6 $1 Qxf5 27. Bd3 e4 28. fxe4 Qxc5+ 29. Qxc5 Rxc5 {Eilmes-Terreaux, corr.
2012. The position is close to a draw, and that was also the final result of
the correspondence mentioned above game. In a practical game, this all is much
harder. White can continue} 30. Rf1 $146 {when there is still some play left,
and Black is the side that has to be accurate.} *

